<h2>Matthew Somerville Morgan (1837-1890): A Life</h2>

<img src="../../../icons2/vntop.gif"/>
<p class="bc">
[<a href ="../../../index.html">Victorian Web Home</a> —> 
<a href="../../index.html">Visual Arts</a> —> 
<a href= "../index.html">Illustration</a> —>
<a href="index.html">Matt Morgan</a>]
</p> 

</div>
	
<div id="main">


<p class="one"><img src="../../../alphabets/monkey.m.gif" height="100" alt="Decorated initial M" border="0" class="floatleft"/>atthew Somerville Morgan (1837-1890) is probably – aside from the men of <span class="periodical">Punch</span> – the best-known and best-studied cartoonist of the Victorian Age. A conservative and aspirational man, but expressing often quite radical views, Morgan’s twin cartoons for <span class="periodical">The Tomahawk</span>, imagining <a href="../../../history/victoria/index.html">Queen Victoria</a> having abandoned the throne, or – worse – allowed her Highland Gillie John Brown to take control, are still well-known today. But they were just one aspect (or two) of a much more variegated career and life-story. — <a href="../../../misc/scully.html">Richard Scully</a></p>

